    <p>Xin chao! My name is Tung Tran.</p>

    <p>I'm a Vietnamese entrepreneur who's been building things on the internet since I was 15.</p>

    <p>I live in Hanoi with my wife, our son, and two corgis.</p>

    <p>This is my personal blog. I started it in 2013 to document my journey — the lessons, the mistakes, and the occasional win. I plan to keep writing here for a long time.</p>

    <h2>What I Do</h2>

    <p>I build and invest in internet businesses.</p>

    <p>Over the years, I've built and sold multiple profitable websites, co-founded a crypto media company, and grown a venture portfolio with 50+ team members and 60+ investments.</p>

    <p>Lately, I've been deep into AI — using it to code, write, and rethink how I work. It's opened up a whole new chapter for me.</p>

    <h2>My Story</h2>

    <p>Here's the short version.</p>

    <p><strong>2006</strong> — Got my first PC as a gift. Changed everything.</p>
    <p><strong>2007</strong> — Taught myself HTML and CSS. Built random websites for fun.</p>
    <p><strong>2010</strong> — Discovered affiliate marketing. Switched from blogging in Vietnamese to English — bigger market, bigger opportunities.</p>
    <p><strong>2011</strong> — Made my first affiliate sale. $118.08. I'll never forget that number.</p>
    <p><strong>2012</strong> — Sold my first blog on Flippa for $3,500. Still in high school.</p>
    <p><strong>2013</strong> — Dropped out of college to go full-time. Everyone thought I was crazy. Started Cloud Living to document the ride.</p>
    <p><strong>2013–2017</strong> — Built niche websites. Some worked, some flopped. Learned more from the failures. Grew a small team and started running things like a real business.</p>
    <p><strong>2018–2019</strong> — Co-founded TK Media with my best friend. Built it into a profitable media company.</p>
    <p><strong>2020</strong> — Everything clicked. All my sites grew at once. First year crossing 7 figures in profit. Sold my largest websites to a major Canadian company by year's end.</p>
    <p><strong>2021</strong> — Pivoted hard into crypto. Renamed the company to TK Ventures. Built media assets, grew the team to 50+, made 60+ blockchain investments. Ended up being my best year financially.</p>
    <p><strong>2022–2023</strong> — Hit the brakes. Focused on health, family, and figuring out what I actually wanted next.</p>
    <p><strong>2024</strong> — Became a dad. That changed everything. Spent the year taking care of my son. Businesses kept running, just at a slower pace.</p>
    <p><strong>2025</strong> — A tough year. Business kept doing well, but almost everything else was hard. Exited a bad real estate deal at a loss. Held too much cash while real estate and stocks boomed around me. Got hacked and lost a significant amount of crypto. Spent too much energy on FOMO and greed. And on top of all that, my dad had a stroke. He's recovering, but it hit me really hard. A humbling year with a lot of expensive lessons.</p>
    <p><strong>2026</strong> — Back in building mode. Using AI heavily — for coding, writing, organizing my life. Feels like the start of something new. Also why I'm writing here again.</p>

    <h2>A Few Things About Me</h2>

    <p><strong>I'm an introvert.</strong> Small groups and real conversations over big events.</p>
    <p><strong>English is my second language.</strong> Writing used to take me forever. AI changed that. Now I focus on the ideas and let the tools handle the polish.</p>
    <p><strong>I value enough.</strong> I've been fortunate. But I learned early that chasing more for the sake of more doesn't lead anywhere good. I'd rather have time, health, and freedom.</p>
    <p><strong>I'm always learning.</strong> A new programming language, a trading strategy, how to keep an aquarium alive — there's always something.</p>
    <p><strong>When I'm not working:</strong> Gaming, yoga, reading, traveling, aquascaping, scuba diving. Lately I've been growing a garden and playing pickleball. The garden is going well. The pickleball... not so much.</p>

    <h2>Why This Blog Exists</h2>

    <p>Cloud Living started as a way to share what I was learning about making money online.</p>
    <p>Over the years, it became something more personal. Now it's just me writing about what I know. No fluff. No guru act. Just real stories from someone who's been at this for over a decade.</p>
    <p>If something I write helps you avoid a mistake or gives you a useful idea — that's enough for me.</p>
    <p>My DMs are always open.</p>
    <p>Cheers!<br />-Tung</p>
